nrigge, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1230–1262":"about 1230–1262","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–Female":"Deceased","1243–1329":"1243–1329","1255–1318":"1255–1318","1260–1303":"1260–1303","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","about 1243":"about 1243","1318":"1318","1329":"1329","about 1230":"about 1230","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Long Clawson, Leicestershire, England":"Long Clawson, Leicestershire, England","Croft, Leicestershire, England":"Croft, Leicestershire, England","Staynwriggis, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Staynnrigge, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richmond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Richmond (North Yorkshire). The placename was probably transferred after the Norman Conquest from any of numerous places in France named with Old French <i>riche</i> ‘mighty, strong’ + <i>munt</i>, <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’. Richmond in southwest London received this name only in the reign of Henry VII, in honor of the king, who had been Earl of Richmond until he came to the throne, and is unlikely to be the source of this surname.","occasionally a variant of   Richman  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>. The two names were probably often confused.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Richman","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Richeman</i>, either from an unrecorded Old English <i>Rīcmann</i>, or from a pet form of <i>Richard</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-man</i>. The name was sometimes interchangeable with   Rickman  , especially in recent times.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>riche</i> ‘rich, powerful’ + <i>-man</i>. Compare   Rich  .","English: perhaps a variant of   Richmond  , or vice versa."]}]},{"name":"Roald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Old Norse <i>hróðr</i> ‘fame’ + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"FitzAlan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name  <i>Alan</i> (  see  Allen  ), ‘son of  <i>Alan</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]},{"name":"Allen","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alan  , in Britain generally found only as a surname, but in North America equally common as a given name."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Roald FitzAlan de Richmond The Elder of Croft was born about 1230, in Croft, Leicestershire, England, his father, Lord Alan Roald de Richmond of Burton Manor, was 22 and his mother, Matilda Goldington, was 22. He married Mrs. Sybil De Richmond. In 1201, his occupation is listed as constable of richmond in Richmond, Yorkshire, England. He died in 1262, in England, at the age of 33."},"et":{"about 1230–1262":"umbes 1230–1262","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–Female":"Surnud","1243–1329":"1243–1329","1255–1318":"1255–1318","1260–1303":"1260–1303","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1230":"1230","1262":"1262","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","about 1243":"umbes 1243","1318":"1318","1329":"1329","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Long Clawson, Leicestershire, England":"Long Clawson, Leicestershire, England","Croft, Leicestershire, England":"Croft, Leicestershire, England","Staynwriggis, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Staynnrigge, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1230–1262":"noin 1230–1262","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–Female":"Kuollut","1243–1329":"1243–1329","1255–1318":"1255–1318","1260–1303":"1260–1303","1210–1271":"1210–1271","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1230":"1230","1262"